            "http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4126/5214569968_6ed766cd08.jpg"
        ],
        "post": " ラーメンWalkerOut of the dozen or so ramen magazines published in Japan, Ramen Walker might be the most famous.  The \"Walker\" name is appended to all manner of things.  If you ever live in Japan, I suggest you pick up a your-city-name-here Walker.This year there's not 1, but 4 for the Tokyo area alone.And 36 in total in Japan.  Each has shop info for a 100 to 200 places. That's a lot of ramen shops.If anyone wants a set, show me the money and I'll pick them up for you!  ",
        "title": " 覆麺 (Junk Style at Fukumen in Jimbocho) "
    },
    {
        "date": "2010-11-21 00:00:00",
        "pictures": [
            "http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4089/5194975398_785d00259e.jpg",
            "http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4084/5194377427_f72f273f58.jpg"
        ],
        "post": " 麺屋 いろはThe Ramen Riders tried to visit my friend's #1 choice one Sunday afternoon.  Always a skeptic about other's opinions, I was reassured that it was a good shop - when we saw the sign out front stating that they were closed - because the soup was sold out.  So we went to another nearby shop, as I didn't really have the time to venture to greener pastures.Tasted like a bland miso with squirts of Thai Sriracha sauce.  Not so good.  Save that sweet spice for your pho.More Shop Info HereView Larger Map  ",
