    {
        "date": "2010-12-21 00:00:00",
        "pictures": [
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5121/5279776375_5268635f5d.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5241/5280380376_ffd19310c3.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5242/5279770023_ec20f495e2.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5126/5279773935_4fb70f4953.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5283/5280377000_29b1031a68.jpg"
        ],
        "post": " 秋葉らーめん 松風I spilled a beer on my keyboard, rendering it useless.  This meant that the next days adventure would be into the heart of Akihabara, the electronic district of the city.I set the bar low for this shop, even though Matsukaze is in every ramen magazine and book, usually near the front.  Akihabara isn't known for it's good food.  Maid cafes, 7-story robot stores, and Ferraris decorated with anime decals - yes.  Great noodles - no.Then I had a taste.  This is an excellent bowl.  Unexpected.The shop blends a typical fish and pork broth with a vegetable puree.  The result is a thick, rich, and maybe even healthy bowl of ramen.Like I said, a big surprise.  The location is down a nondescript alley along a street reserved for discount computer supplies.  And if you are in the same boat as me, you'll be happy to know that there is a store about a minute away from Matsukaze selling nothing but keyboards.Official Site HereView Larger Map  ",
        "title": " 松風 (Matsukaze in Akihabara) "
    },
    {
        "date": "2010-12-21 00:00:00",
        "pictures": [
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5242/5279768215_fec914dea3.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5130/5279766955_006b393697.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5045/5279758033_71fc157d39.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5287/5279761737_316aa6e1b5.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5083/5280370660_7edf2ae1ce.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5086/5279763819_6fc4751442.jpg"
        ],
        "post": " Nagi Nicai is a very relaxing place in the evenings.  Almost like an izakaya.  But for lunch, it's a busy tsukemen shop.All they have on the menu is tsukemen.  You can choose regular noodles, or the shops homemade momen.  Feeling adventurous, both Daniel and I went with the unknown.A nice touch is the bowl of pickled ginger to cleanse your palette.I had the meat version, with an excellent piece of grilled chicken.The momen noodles are wide and long.  It's like eating lasagna noodles.  A unique bowl indeed.The taste was good, but a bit hard to eat.  If I came back for lunch I'd get the regular noodles.Official Site HereView Larger Map  ",
        "title": " 松風 (Matsukaze in Akihabara) "
    },
    {
        "date": "2010-12-14 00:00:00",
        "pictures": [
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5009/5257259818_ed9f666512.jpg",
            "http://farm6.static.flickr.com/5168/5256644629_f3cb212d0b.jpg",
