        "post": " ジャジャンハウスKorean-style Chinese food in Japan.  That sums up Jyajyan House in Okubo.Okubo is Tokyo's Korea-town, for those out of the loop.  But like the Yokohama China-town, it has taken on an uber-touristy feel.  With the boom of K-pop fandom in Japan (I'm looking at you mid 30s to 50s Japanese housewives!) the place is a bit of a madhouse these days.  I'm talking fleets of tour buses at noon on a weekday.There are plenty of Korean staples.  Yakiniku, bibimbap, and chijimi shops along the whole block.  There are even a few places to get ramyeon, that Korean cousin of ramen.Most Korean noodle spots here use instant noodles.  Not interested.Apart from the kimchi, this isn't very Korean***.  True to the sign on the shop's door, this is Chinese with a Korean twist.  The noodles are hand made on site, lamein style.***I shouldn't make assumptions about Korea, since I know very little about noodle culture there.  According to a reader's comment, this combo is quite common in Korea, and is maybe the quintessential Korean-Chinese noodle dish.Probably the number one item on the menu is the double plate of jyajyamen and champon.  The champon is chock full of strange seafood bits.  Strange by a Western standard.  But, remember, this is Korean-style Chinese food in Japan.  That's a lot of east.And, they deliver.View Larger Map東京都新宿区歌舞伎町2-32-17Tokyo, Shinjuku-ku, Kabukicho 2-32-17Closest station: Shin-OkuboOpen 11:00-3:00am  ",
